Title : Vahik Pirhamzei
Text : '''Vahik Pirhamzei''' ({{lang-fa|واهیک پیرحمزه ای}}, {{lang-hy|Վահիկ Փիրհամզեյի}}, born November 6, 1968) is an [[Iranian Armenians|Iranian-Armenian]] actor, producer, director and writer who produces works in English, Armenian and [[Persian language|Persian]]. His film [[My Uncle Rafael]], released in 2012 which was based after his play "Rafael Keroo Gandzere", earned him recognition and awards.

== Early life ==
Before moving to the [[United States]] in 1989, Vahik Pirhamzei lived in the suburbs of [[Tehran]]. He began drawing extensively when he was ten years old and later became involved in various forms of visual arts. He performed stories and puppet shows for his family and friends.

After the fall of the [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Shah]] and the Pahlavi dynasty in 1978-79, Vahik was forced to leave his hometown. He moved to [[Mettmann, Germany]] in 1988, where he registered for painting classes in local schools.

Vahik arrived in [[Los Angeles]] in 1989, engaging in auditions and freelance work on cable TV programs for Iranian viewers in Southern [[California]]. He wrote, directed, and starred in various comedy sketches such as; "Nika's Café", "The Specialist" and "Moshkelat.com" depicting the immigrant life in Los Angeles. He appeared in over 300 of his own comedy skits. Since then, Vahik has contributed widely to the Iranian community theatre in L.A. He has starred in more than 25 stage productions, as well as performed in various locations throughout the United States, [[Canada]], and [[Europe]].

== Career ==
After Vahik's first original production "Sky Blue" was staged in Los Angeles, he began receiving offers to present more of his work. He directed several music videos for Iranian, Armenian, and other Middle Eastern artists. He worked with L.A. Iranian artists, including [[Moein (Singer)|Moein]], [[Googoosh]], [[Dariush Eghbali|Dariush]], Kamran & Hooman, Armenian pop musicians [[Armenchik]] and [[Tata Simonyan]] and Russian star [[Kristina Orbakaitė]].

In 2000 Pirhamzei debuted "The Richmond Comedy Club" on TV. In 2004, he launched a weekly entertainment magazine news show called "World Entertainment Connections".

Vahik staged his play "''Mez Lavootchoon Chi Egell''" ("Nothing Good Has Come Our Way"). Vahik played his best known character, ''Rafael Keri'' (Uncle Rafael), a 72-year-old, quick-witted Armenian senior living in L.A. Two spin-off productions called "''Rafel Keroo Gandzer'e''" ("The Treasures of Uncle Rafael")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbarez.com/124535/theater-review-%E2%80%98rafael%E2%80%99s-treasures%E2%80%99-rich-in-comedy/|title=Theater Review: 'Rafael's Treasures' Rich in Comedy|work=Asbarez News|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> and its sequel;  "''Rafael Keroo Bardez''" ("Uncle Rafael's Garden") took the stage, depicting the life of Uncle Rafael and his dysfunctional, yet amusing family. Vahik wrote, produced, directed, and starred in both productions.

In 2010, Pirhamzei released a new play called ''Man Ravanshenas Lazem Nadaram'' ("I Don't Need a Psychologist"). In the year that followed (2011), he wrote yet another play "Honest Liars"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbarez.com/101052/theater-review-the-truth-about-%E2%80%98honest-liars%E2%80%99/|title=THEATER REVIEW: The Truth About 'Honest Liars'|work=Asbarez News|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://asbarez.com/122535/vahik-pirhamzei-presents-his-first-english-language-play-%E2%80%98unusual-heroes%E2%80%99/NR97347] {{dead link|date=October 2014}}</ref> and then followed it up with "Experienced Liars" in 2012.

Later in 2012, Pirhamzei wrote, directed, and produced "Don't Say Goodbye", short film/music video with [[Eric Roberts]] for [[Googoosh]]. He also wrote, directed, and produced "Ejaz" (Miracle) for Googoosh in 2012.

In 2012, Pirhamzei co-wrote a spin-off of "The Garden of Uncle Rafael" with Scott Yagemann as a feature film, [[My Uncle Rafael]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbarez.com/103811/my-uncle-rafael-set-for-theatrical-release-on-september-21/|title='My Uncle Rafael' Set for Theatrical Release on September 21|work=Asbarez News|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081114/http://asbarez.com/103811/my-uncle-rafael-set-for-theatrical-release-on-september-21/|archive-date=2014-10-06|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> The film included cast members  [[John Michael Higgins]], [[Missi Pyle]] and [[Rachel Blanchard]] and was directed by Marc Fusco, who formerly worked with [[Steven Spielberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/sep/29/entertainment/et-week-stealing29|title=Article on Marc Fusco in LA times|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006121928/http://articles.latimes.com/2003/sep/29/entertainment/et-week-stealing29|archive-date=2014-10-06|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref name="salamtoronto">"Pirhamzei takes Iranian, Armenian cultures to Hollywood" article in [http://salamtoronto.ca/?p=2402 "Salam Toronto" Newspaper] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006070232/http://salamtoronto.ca/?p=2402 |date=2014-10-06 }}</ref> The film followed a desperate TV producer convincing an old Armenian Uncle to star in a reality show. Cultures clash when Uncle Rafael is thrown into the Schumacher family household, a dysfunctional American family in the midst of falling apart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/award-winning_comedy_my_uncle_rafael_lands_home_at_slater_brothers_entertai|title="My Uncle Rafael" article on Indiwire|author=Nigel M Smith|date=3 October 2011|work=Indiewire|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006110210/http://www.indiewire.com/article/award-winning_comedy_my_uncle_rafael_lands_home_at_slater_brothers_entertai|archive-date=2014-10-06|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref> Pirhmazei won the Best Screenplay and Best Actor Awards from ARPA International Film Festival for [[My Uncle Rafael]]. It also earned the Best Director Award for Marc Fusco.<ref name="salamtoronto" /><ref name="arpa">Arpa Film Festival Winners article in [http://asbarez.com/98346/arpa-film-festival-award-winners-announced Asbarez Newspaper] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009131247/http://asbarez.com/98346/arpa-film-festival-award-winners-announced/ |date=2014-10-09 }}</ref>

In 2013 Vahik Pirhamzei wrote, directed, and starred in the feature film "Guardian Angel" and won Golden Pom Award from Pomegranate Film Festival Awards in Toronto.<ref name="pom">{{cite web|url=http://pomegranatefilmfestival.com/guardian-angel-usa-105-min-directed-by-vahik-pirhamzei-world-premiere/|title=Pomegranate Film Festival - November 5-9, 2014   GUARDIAN ANGEL – USA – 105 min. – directed by Vahik Pirhamzei – North American Premiere|publisher=Pomegeanatefilmfestival.com|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530231806/http://pomegranatefilmfestival.com/guardian-angel-usa-105-min-directed-by-vahik-pirhamzei-world-premiere/|archive-date=2014-05-30|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armenianpulse.com/2013/06/vahik-pirhamzeis-new-movie-guardian-angel-set-to-begin-production-on-june-18/|title=Vahik Pirhamzei's New Movie 'Guardian Angel' Set to Begin Production on June 18|work=Armenian Pulse Radio & Entertainment|accessdate=4 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006070655/http://www.armenianpulse.com/2013/06/vahik-pirhamzeis-new-movie-guardian-angel-set-to-begin-production-on-june-18/|archive-date=2014-10-06|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>
In 2013 Pirhamzei directed and produced a music video for Russian actress [[Kristina Orbakaitė]] and Armenian pop singer [[Tata Simonyan|Tata]].

In 2014, Pirhamzei completed his full-length feature film "Guardian Angel".

In 2016, Pirhamzei filmed "3 Weeks in Yerevan" oversees in Armenia. The movie premiered in Armenia and United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/06/15/3-weeks-in-yerevan/|title=Berberian, Pirhamzei, and Tokhatyan's '3 Weeks in Yerevan' Coming Soon|date=15 June 2016|access-date=2016-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112081317/http://armenianweekly.com/2016/06/15/3-weeks-in-yerevan/|archive-date=2016-11-12|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/arpa-foundation-presents-u-premiere-115100669.html|title=ARPA Foundation Presents: The U.S. Premiere of '3 Weeks in Yerevan' in Los Angeles|date=20 August 2016|access-date=2017-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112083115/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/arpa-foundation-presents-u-premiere-115100669.html#|archive-date=2016-11-12|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

In October 2016 Vahik brought his play "Look Me in The Eye" to the stage with the collaboration between the actors from Armenia, [[Luiza Nersisyan]] and [[Sos Janibekyan]] with the diaspora Armenian actors, Anahid Avanesian and himself created a refreshing dynamic on stage for the Los Angeles Armenian community of theater goers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armenianpulse.com/2016/10/pirhamzeis-latest-play-delights-audiences/|title=Pirhamzei's Latest Play Delights Audiences|date=30 October 2016|access-date=2016-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120065716/http://www.armenianpulse.com/2016/10/pirhamzeis-latest-play-delights-audiences/|archive-date=2018-01-20|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>

